entry.title: [Waffle] Support for high DPI icons
entry.content:
Old behavior on desktop:

- google used 24px icon, possibly upscaled for HiDPI (very blurry)

- other search engines used 96px downscaled (slightly blurry)



Old behavior on iOS:

- all icons were downscaled from 96px



New behavior on choice screen:

All engines use 24px on low DPI and 48px on high DPI on desktop.

iOS uses 48px or 72px depending on the screen.

Icons are no longer scaled.



In desktop settings:

icons are downscaled from 48px to 16px or 32px (depending on screen dpi).



Choice screens, zoomed-in comparison:

https://screenshot.googleplex.com/3hCE9kjfxpY8Qya



Settings, zoomed-in comparison:

https://screenshot.googleplex.com/4xZ9cux98DjCHa4

Uses 48px downscaled to 16 or 32, `image-set` not supported.

entry.title: "Fix" string issue in page_load_in_process_fuzzer.
entry.content:
This fuzzer was previously reporting an error because it was

manipulating a string returned as the root URL from a web server which

had failed to start.



If the web server fails to start, the fuzzer should just exit

immediately instead. That was the previous intention, but we weren't

doing it correctly.



The actual failure to start is probably caused by a lack of runtime

deps, which will be rectified separately in due course by this CL and

subsequent:

https://github.com/google/clusterfuzz/pull/3515

Meanwhile treat such failures as fatal, so we don't run into problems

later.

being handled. With this CL, DecommitAndZeroSystemPages now returns a

boolean, giving the caller the ability to handle the error.

entry.title: Remove (Test)AutofillTickClock
entry.content:
In unit tests time can be mocked using a base::test::TaskEnvironment,

as described here [1]. According to [2], the pattern of defining custom

clocks is not preferred anymore.



In Autofill, (Test)Autofill(Tick)Clock exist, which default to the

current Time(Tick) in production code, but can be mocked in tests using

the test clocks. This CL makes takes the first step to move away from

them, by removing (Test)AutofillTickClock and migrating tests to a

TaskEnvironment with MOCK_TIME. Follow-up CLs can make similar changes

to get rid of (Test)AutofillClock (which has even more uses).



From a technical perspective, this CL:

- Ran ./tools/git/mffr.py "AutofillTickClock::NowTicks\(\)"

"base::TimeTicks::Now()"

- Removed (test_)autofill_tick_clock.(cc|h).

- Added MOCK_TIME TaskEnvironments to all relevant test fixtures.

- Replaced calls to TestAutofillTickClock::Advance() with calls to

TaskEnvironment::FastForwardBy().

- Converted calls to TestAutofillTickClock::SetNow() with calls to

equivalent calls to TaskEnvironment::FastForwardBy() (fortunately, no

test relied on moving time backwards).

- Fixed any tests that relied on non-mocked time: By adding the

TaskEnvironment to the test fixture, all tests using that fixture

use MOCK_TIME. This broke some tests - see Gerrit comments.

- Removed the Autofill presubmit warning suggesting to use

AutofillTickClock.



[1] https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/main:base/test/task_environment.h;l=104-121;drc=0b7de4926a111cee0bdfd0aca0ce99a5e208b771

[2]¬†https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/main:base/time/tick_clock.h;l=17-20;drc=8e78783dc1f7007bad46d657c9f332614e240fd8

entry.title: Exclude HeuristicSource::kLegacy from non-active patterns
entry.content:
A HeuristicSource describes a mechanism to get heuristic predictions,

which is currently either ML or regexes. Due to pattern provider,

which can provide different regex definitions, "regexes" is split

further into different PatternSources.



The active HeuristicSource defines the mechanism that's used to compute

the fields' heuristic types used in production (the one that will

influence the overall type used for filling).



The non-active HeuristicSources are defined as the set of all available

HeuristicSources, except the active HeuristicSource. The PatternSources

among these non-active HeuristicSources are used to compute shadow

predictions for the kAutofillParsingPatternProvider experiment.



What exactly all available HeuristicSources are depends on build flags

and feature flags, and this CL changes that definition.



Generally:

- HeuristicSource::kMachineLearning is only available when

kAutofillModelPredictions is enabled.

- HeuristicSource::kDefault, HeuristicSource::kExperimental and

HeuristicSource::kNextGen are only available in Chrome branded builds

when kAutofillParsingPatternProvider is enabled.

- HeuristicSource::kLegacy is always available.



This CL removes HeuristicSource::kLegacy from the available patterns in

Chrome branded builds when kAutofillParsingPatternProvider is enabled.

This is desirable for a few reasons:

- Chrome branded builds with kAutofillParsingPatternProvider are not

using the kLegacy patterns, not even for shadow metrics. They are

intended to be lower-quality regexes for non-Chrome branded builds.

- Since they are currently part of the non-active HeuristicSources,

they take up additional computational resources during parsing.



Bug: 1479353

entry.title: Fix ProfileTokenQuality::AddObservation() CHECK() failure
entry.content:
In AddObservation(type) the CHECK() that type is among the supported

types of *profile_ is failing (even after crrev.com/c/5169107 - see

linked crash report in the bug). This seemed strange, since the very

same check is performed earlier in the call stack in

AddObservationsForFilledForm().



Turns out the bug is in AddSubsetOfObservations(observatiosn), which is

supposed to only add a random subset of observations for privacy

reasons. The function works by randomly shuffeling the observations and

calling AddObservation() for the first k, where k is the result of a

function agreed upon with privacy. While computing k, the code

unfortunately references not only observations, but also observations_,

the member variable storing the already existing observations. As a

result, k can be larger than observations, causing code below to reach

out of memory, adding garbage observations of not necessarily

supported types.



This is actually a test for this case, but it had a bug too: The test

created a form with 12 different types, filled it with a complete

profile and submitted. It expected that only k = 8 (instead of the usual

k = 12 - 3 = 9 for "regular" sized forms) observations get added.

Turns out that one of the fields got dropped by some filtering logic

earlier, since it wasn't filled, because the "complete" profile doesn't

have two last names. Instead, the now uses NAME_MIDDLE and NAME_LAST,

which the profile has.



Fixed: 1515409

entry.title: Avoid sending variations for Orca product ID.
entry.content:
For privacy, we do not want to collect variations for Orca. Right now,

variations is included in all reports.



Because reports can be loaded from disk, whether we include variations

or not for a report should be persisted to disk. However, it is too

complicated to modify how reports are persisted to disk.



Therefore, we hardcode the product IDs where we do not want to collect

variations. A FeedbackReport now takes in the product ID as well.



Note: We could've directly taken a boolean in FeedbackReport to

control whether variations should be included (instead of indirectly

via product ID). But FeedbackReport's constructors are called from

two places: one in FeedbackReport and one in FeedbackUploader. So

this approach means we need the product ID check in two different

places, which is bad. Therefore, we just pass the product ID and

check it once in FeedbackReport.

details are still TBD (e.g. how many gifs can be shown, whether to

always animate or only animate on hover, resolution requirements), so

just add some basic functionality to experiment with for now.

service, via ash::image_util API. The decoded frames are stored in

entry.title: Add bridge to propagate file change service events from Lacros to Ash.
entry.content:
This CL adds a bridge to propagate file change service events from

Lacros to Ash over crosapi. The specific event propagated in this CL is

`OnFileCreatedFromShowSaveFilePicker()` which occurs when a file is

created in fulfillment of a `window.showSaveFilePicker()` request.



Events are delivered to the `FileChangeService` in Ash where they are
